{"id":13,"date":"2020-10-15T02:40:20","date_gmt":"2020-10-15T02:40:20","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/?page_id=13"},"modified":"2022-02-03T13:42:43","modified_gmt":"2022-02-03T18:42:43","slug":"about","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/about\/","title":{"rendered":"About us"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:37% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1028\" height=\"887\" src=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/02\/PCL_Final-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-292 size-full\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/02\/PCL_Final-1.png 1028w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/02\/PCL_Final-1-300x259.png 300w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/02\/PCL_Final-1-1024x884.png 1024w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/02\/PCL_Final-1-768x663.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 89vw, (max-width: 1000px) 54vw, (max-width: 1071px) 543px, 580px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">We are a group of parents committed to fighting for our kids. We&#8217;re concerned about climate. We don&#8217;t care what your politics are; we want you to join us. <\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">We&#8217;re currently in the process of expanding our Expert Advisory Council, building a Steering Committee and are always looking for parents to join as volunteers for our local chapters.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-container-4 wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<div class=\"wp-container-3 wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-container-1 wp-block-column\">\n<p><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Michael Leifman, Co-founder and Executive Director<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"http:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Leifman-Michael-7870_Web-ready-1-edited.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-154\" width=\"297\" height=\"223\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Leifman-Michael-7870_Web-ready-1-edited.jpg 800w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Leifman-Michael-7870_Web-ready-1-edited-300x225.jpg 300w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Leifman-Michael-7870_Web-ready-1-edited-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 297px) 100vw, 297px\" \/><figcaption>Michael Leifman<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">Michael is fighting to protect his two sons, ages 19 and 14.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Michael is the founding principal of Tenley Consulting, which provides advisory services on a wide landscape of complex issues, including clean energy &amp; environmental policy and economics, forecasting and technology innovation. Michael\u2019s clients range from cleantech startups to \u201chousehold name\u201d environmental NGOs, international energy companies, and the World Bank. Before founding Tenley he was the Senior Strategist for GE\u2019s Business Innovations group and the Principal Strategist for GE Power, where he was responsible for injecting strategic thinking across businesses, raising new ideas, opportunities, and risks to senior leadership, and forcing attention on the non-obvious. Michael joined GE in 2008, and for many years was the Director of Forecasting &amp; Analytics for GE Power &amp; Water. In this role, he developed a reputation not just for analytical rigor but also consensus building. Prior to GE, Michael worked for the U.S. federal government, as the lead analyst in U.S. Department of Energy\u2019s Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy, and as a climate policy and economics analyst at U.S. EPA. He also worked for an environmental policy consulting firm analyzing a diverse set of issues, from chicken waste to the Kyoto Protocol. Michael is also co-host of M4Edge, a podcast on technology startups and the economy. Michael holds an MS in Environmental Sciences, and an MS and a BA in Public Policy.<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-container-2 wp-block-column\">\n<p><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Laurie Moskowitz, Co-Founder and Chief Strategist<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"http:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Laurie-photo-edited-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-153\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\"\/><figcaption>Laurie Moskowitz<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">Laurie is fighting to protect her two sons, ages 19 and 17.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Laurie is the founder of LORE Strategies, a strategic consulting firm in Washington, D.C. Laurie&#8217;s work straddles the intersection of politics and advocacy with a focus on campaign strategy, grassroots organizing, and partnership development. Prior to founding LORE Strategies Laurie served as the Senior Director for U.S. Campaigns for The ONE Campaign, an advocacy group dedicated to fighting extreme poverty, founded by Bono of U2. She was the founder of FieldWorks, one of the nation\u2019s premiere grassroots communications and field strategy firms, where she ran hundreds of grassroots campaigns for candidates and state political parties, advocacy organizations, and ballot initiatives. She has also served the Democratic Party and numerous candidates. She was the first-ever Voter Contact Director at the Democratic National Committee, specializing in micro-targeting and engagement of voters. And in 2000, she served as both the Delegate Director and then the National Coordinated Campaign Director for then-Vice President Al Gore, driving Democratic turnout across the country that was largely credited for winning Al Gore the popular vote. Laurie went on to have senior roles with the presidential campaigns of Kerry, Clinton, and Obama. Laurie originally got her start as an environmental organizer with the PIRGs and what is today known as Environment America. Laurie hails from Northern California and received her BA from University of California at Berkeley. <\/p>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:21% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"262\" height=\"262\" src=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Juan-Declet-Barreto-Headshot.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-227 size-thumbnail\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Juan-Declet-Barreto-Headshot.jpeg 262w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Juan-Declet-Barreto-Headshot-150x150.jpeg 150w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Juan-Declet-Barreto-Headshot-100x100.jpeg 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 262px) 100vw, 262px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Juan Declet-Barreto,  member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Juan Declet-Barreto is a Senior Social Scientist for Climate Vulnerability at Union of Concerned Scientists. Dr. Declet-Barreto earned a Ph.D. in environmental social sciences, M.A. and B.S. degrees in geography, and an associate\u2019s degree in geographic information systems, from Arizona State University. At UCS, his research analyzes and finds solutions to the unequal human health and livelihood impacts of environmental hazards, particularly those exacerbated by climate change. Before joining UCS, Dr. Declet-Barreto spent two years as a climate and health research fellow with the Natural Resources Defense Council, where he helped link climate change to adverse health impacts, with a special attention on low-income communities, and communities populated predominantly by people of color. His research maps, analyzes, and finds solutions to the unequal human health and livelihood impacts of environmental hazards, particularly those exacerbated by climate change. Juan is fighting to protect his two children.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:21% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"708\" height=\"667\" src=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/Todd-Johnston-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-238 size-thumbnail\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/Todd-Johnston-2.jpg 708w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/Todd-Johnston-2-300x283.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 708px) 100vw, 708px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Todd Johnston,  member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Todd Johnston is vice president of policy at ConservAverica, a non-profit organization dedicated to developing and promoting market-oriented solutions to environment and conservation challenges. Prior to joining ConservAmerica, Todd&nbsp;served as Executive Vice President of Government Affairs at the Portland Cement Association, where he led the industries\u2019 federal public policy engagement activities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Todd has served in various senior roles on Capitol Hill,&nbsp;spearheading legislative and oversight programs for the&nbsp;House Science Committee\u2019s Environment and Energy Subcommittee&nbsp;and Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works.&nbsp;Todd also has extensive industry experience: he led the National Mining Association\u2019s air quality regulatory program; before that, he served as the Environment, Health, and Safety Director for Kyanite Mining Corporation, managing all&nbsp;state and federal regulatory compliance and reclamation activities for the company\u2019s various processing plants and mining operations.&nbsp;Todd began his career at the Virginia Department of Environmental Quality, where he drafted and made recommendations on regulatory and statutory language implementing federal and state environmental requirements.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:21% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"580\" height=\"579\" src=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/08\/LaDonna_Northington_sq.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-247 size-thumbnail\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/08\/LaDonna_Northington_sq.jpg 580w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/08\/LaDonna_Northington_sq-300x300.jpg 300w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/08\/LaDonna_Northington_sq-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/08\/LaDonna_Northington_sq-100x100.jpg 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 580px) 100vw, 580px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">LaDonna Northington,  member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">LaDonna Northington is the Associate Dean of Academic Affairs for the School of Nursing.&nbsp; During her tenure at the SON, Dr. Northington has served in various leadership roles, including as a undergraduate program director and assistant dean. Dr. Northington earned her BSN and MSN from the University of Mississippi, School of Nursing and her DNS with an emphasis in Child Health Nursing and Consultations from Louisiana State University. Dr. Northington\u2019s past clinical practice has been in critical care, primarily pediatrics, but adult ICU and ER. Currently she works part time in a pediatric ambulatory clinic.Dr. Northington has publications in peer-reviewed journals and podium presentations on the subjects of pediatric patient care, education and research. Dr. Northington is a member of several professional organizations, and has held several leadership roles in these organizations. Dr. Northington is currently the President of the Society of Pediatric Nurses.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\"> <\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:21% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Jessica-Moerman-Headshot_2019_cropped-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-230 size-thumbnail\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Jessica-Moerman-Headshot_2019_cropped-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Jessica-Moerman-Headshot_2019_cropped-300x300.jpg 300w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Jessica-Moerman-Headshot_2019_cropped-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Jessica-Moerman-Headshot_2019_cropped-768x768.jpg 768w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Jessica-Moerman-Headshot_2019_cropped-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Jessica-Moerman-Headshot_2019_cropped-100x100.jpg 100w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/Jessica-Moerman-Headshot_2019_cropped.jpg 1844w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 89vw, (max-width: 1000px) 54vw, (max-width: 1071px) 543px, 580px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Jessica Moerman,  member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Jessica Moerman is a climate and environmental scientist, a church leader and co-founder of Grace Capital City church, and serves as the Senior Director for Science and Policy at the Evangelical Environmental Network (EEN), the largest evangelical group in the nation with the ministry to care for God&#8217;s creation, engaging more than 3 million Christians in climate action over the last five years. Prior to joining EEN, Jessica served as a AAAS Science and Technology Policy Fellow at the U.S. Department of Energy\u2019s Office of Science. Jessica received her Ph.D. in Earth and Atmospheric Sciences from the Georgia Institute of Technology and has held research positions at the John Hopkins University, University of Michigan, and the Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History, where she researched how climate changed throughout Earth\u2019s history. She has received numerous nationally competitive research awards, including the National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowship and National Science Foundation Postdoctoral Research Fellowship. She has appeared on the NBC TODAY Show, Christian Broadcasting Network, Newsmax, and nationally syndicated radio talk shows, speaking about climate change, the clean energy transition, environmental stewardship, and the intersection of science and faith, and has been featured in the Washington Post and Christianity Today. Jessica is passionate about leading churches and communities towards positive solutions to safeguard our cities, neighborhoods, and the next generation from the effects of a warming world. Jessica is fighting to protect her six-year-old son.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:21% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"484\" height=\"484\" src=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/03\/SPacheco-photo-2015_square-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-223 size-thumbnail\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/03\/SPacheco-photo-2015_square-1.jpg 484w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/03\/SPacheco-photo-2015_square-1-300x300.jpg 300w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/03\/SPacheco-photo-2015_square-1-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/03\/SPacheco-photo-2015_square-1-100x100.jpg 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 484px) 100vw, 484px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Susan Pacheco,  member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Susan Pacheco<strong> <\/strong>is an Associate Professor at the University of Texas Health Science Center, where she specializes in pediatric asthma, allergy, and immunology. Dr. Pacheco is focused on educating people about the threats to human health associated with climate change. She trained with the Climate Reality Project, founded the Alliance of Health Professionals Against Climate Change, as well as the Texas Coalition for Climate Change Awareness, an organization formed by diverse community groups and individuals. Dr. Pacheco recently authored research showing that pregnant women exposed to heat and air pollution are at heightened risk of adverse pregnancy outcomes.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:21% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"http:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Sparkman-photo-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-196 size-thumbnail\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Sparkman-photo-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Sparkman-photo-100x100.jpg 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Gregg Sparkman,  member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Gregg Sparkman is a postdoctoral research associate in the Andlinger Center for Energy and the Environment at Princeton University. His research is focused on understanding social change, including the causes and consequences of norms shifting over time in behavior and policy attitudes. He completed his PhD at Stanford University in social psychology, where he investigated how people are influenced by witnessing social change and how this can be incorporated into interventions in social, environmental, and political domains. Collaborating with non-profit, public, and private organizations, he uses national surveys and field studies on behavior to develop and assess social psychological interventions to meet social and environmental goals.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:20% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"213\" height=\"226\" src=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/Krysta-headshot-2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-239 size-full\"\/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Krysta Villeda, member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Krysta Villeda is the Chief of Staff at Project Pulso, a nonprofit digital media startup reaching more than 1 million Latinos in the U.S. with the mission of increasing this community&#8217;s political power. Prior to joining Pulso, Krysta was a Principal in the Tech, Media, and Telecom (TMT) practice at Kaiser Associates, a strategy consulting firm in Washington, D.C. At Kaiser, Krysta partnered with C-suite clients in the South American Telecom industry, leading project teams focused on business process design and implementation, process improvement, system implementation, change management and organizational design. She also led strategy engagements across the TMT and financial services practices. Krysta worked with several nonprofits throughout her academic&nbsp;career, working on analyzing climate finance programs, developing community programs, and evaluating the potential of farm-to-school programs to serve as catalysts for food equity. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Krysta holds a M.A. in Latin American Studies from Georgetown University&#8217;s School of Foreign Service (with a concentration in political economy). She also holds B.A.s in Global Economics and Environmental Studies and a minor in Latin American and Latino Studies from the University of California, Santa Cruz. Krysta is a proud Angeleno, having been born and raised in LA, and has lived in Washington, D.C. since 2012.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:20% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"350\" height=\"350\" src=\"http:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/David-Waskow-photo.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-156 size-full\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/David-Waskow-photo.jpg 350w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/David-Waskow-photo-300x300.jpg 300w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/David-Waskow-photo-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/David-Waskow-photo-100x100.jpg 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">David Waskow, founding member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">David is the Director of the International Climate Initiative at the World Resources Institute (WRI), a leading international think tank. The Initiative is focused on international cooperation that can catalyze action on climate change at the national level around the world. David is widely known and respected in the climate community as a voice for climate action and equity. Before joining WRI, David was the Climate Change Program Director for Oxfam America and was the International Program Director at Friends of the Earth-U.S. David holds an MPA in Public Policy, an MA in Religion, and a BA in History.  David is fighting to protect his 21-year-old son and his 19-year-old daughter.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:20% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1024\" height=\"996\" src=\"http:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Robin-W-photo3-1024x996.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-165 size-full\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Robin-W-photo3-1024x996.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Robin-W-photo3-300x292.jpg 300w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Robin-W-photo3-768x747.jpg 768w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/11\/Robin-W-photo3.jpg 1123w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 89vw, (max-width: 1000px) 54vw, (max-width: 1071px) 543px, 580px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Robin Wiener, founding member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Robin is the President of the Institute for Scrap Recycling Industries, the trade association representing the $100 billion recycling industry. Robin leads ISRI\u2019s staff of 47 professionals, promoting safe, economically sustainable and environmentally responsible recycling through networking, advocacy, and education. As ISRI\u2019s chief executive since 1997, Robin has extensive experience in nonprofit management, board relations, and advocacy on the state, national, and international levels. She currently serves on the boards of Keep America Beautiful, Sustainable Electronics Recycling International, and Jason Learning, and is a Past President of the National Association of Manufacturers\u2019 Council of Manufacturing Associations and sits on the Key Industry Associations Committee of the American Society of Association Executives. Prior to ISRI, Robin worked at ICF International, providing environmental consulting and risk management services to private and public sector clients. Robin holds a JD and a BS in Chemical Engineering. Robin is fighting to protect her two daughters, ages 17 and 12.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile is-vertically-aligned-top\" style=\"grid-template-columns:20% auto\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"299\" height=\"299\" src=\"http:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/Don-Wuebbles-head-shot.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-188 size-full\" srcset=\"https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/Don-Wuebbles-head-shot.png 299w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/Don-Wuebbles-head-shot-150x150.png 150w, https:\/\/parentsclimateleague.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/Don-Wuebbles-head-shot-100x100.png 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 299px) 100vw, 299px\" \/><\/figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\">\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\"><mark style=\"background-color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)\" class=\"has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-amber-color\">Don Wuebbles, member, Expert Advisory Council<\/mark><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">Don Wuebbles is the Harry E. Preble Professor of Atmospheric Science at the University of Illinois.  From 2015 to early 2017, Dr. Wuebbles was Assistant Director with the Office of Science and Technology Policy at the Executive Office of the President in Washington DC, where he was the White House expert on climate science. He was Head of the Department of Atmospheric Sciences at the University of Illinois from 1994 to 2006. Dr. Wuebbles is an expert in atmospheric physics and chemistry, with over 500 scientific publications related to the Earth\u2019s climate, air quality, and the stratospheric ozone layer. However, his work goes well beyond that through providing analyses and development of metrics used in national and international policy and in developing analyses for understanding climate impacts on society and ecosystems, plus potential resilience and societal responses. He has been a leader in a number of international and national scientific assessments, including being a Coordinating Lead Author on several international climate assessments led by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) that resulted in IPCC being awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2007. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-small-font-size\">He co-led the first volume of the 4th U.S. National Climate Assessment published in November 2017 that assesses the science of climate change and its effects on the United States. He led a new assessment on the<br>impacts of climate change on the Great Lakes that was published in March 2019 and he is currently leading a special assessment of the impacts of climate change on the state of Illinois. Dr. Wuebbles has received major<br>awards, including the Cleveland Abbe Award from the American Meteorological Society, the Stratospheric Ozone Protection Award from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, and the Bert Bolin Global Environmental Change Award from the American Geophysical Union He is a Fellow of three major professional science societies, the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the American Geophysical Union, and the American Meteorological Society .<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n<\/div><\/div>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>We are a group of parents committed to fighting for our kids. We&#8217;re concerned about climate. We don&#8217;t care what your politics are; we want you to join us. We&#8217;re currently in the process of expanding our Expert Advisory Council, building a Steering 